easily create great checkout

00:00:34.050 --> 00:00:37.460
experiences to
get great results.

00:00:37.460 --> 00:00:41.030
Through watching many usability
studies over the years,

00:00:41.030 --> 00:00:44.030
I'm well aware that
e-commerce experiences

00:00:44.030 --> 00:00:48.110
can be the high points
of frustration for users.

00:00:48.110 --> 00:00:50.510
That's because they're
often the low points

00:00:50.510 --> 00:00:53.690
of the entire
shopping experience.

00:00:53.690 --> 00:00:56.640
There's friction everywhere.

00:00:56.640 --> 00:01:00.980
You start typing in information,
but something's wrong, right?

00:01:00.980 --> 00:01:03.660
Red errors appear in
the forms, addresses

00:01:03.660 --> 00:01:05.970
don't match so you try again.

00:01:05.970 --> 00:01:09.510
You add your credit card
number, but it's wrong.

00:01:09.510 --> 00:01:11.640
And so you try that again.

00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:14.820
You need to create an
account, but the password

00:01:14.820 --> 00:01:16.834
isn't strong enough
and you get told that

00:01:16.834 --> 00:01:18.000
and you need to think again.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.200
Or the two passwords don't match
or you already have a password

00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:25.530
but you can't remember it.

00:01:25.530 --> 00:01:28.440
Every one of these
experiences represents

00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:32.670
an opportunity for a user
to decide it's not worth it.

00:01:32.670 --> 00:01:35.550
At every red error, at
every point of friction,

00:01:35.550 --> 00:01:37.710
users can abandon
their purchase.

00:01:37.710 --> 00:01:40.980
This results in lost sales
for retailers and lots

00:01:40.980 --> 00:01:43.300
of irritation for users.

00:01:43.300 --> 00:01:45.720
In fact, we recently
did an audit

00:01:45.720 --> 00:01:48.840
in Europe of more
than 400 top sites

00:01:48.840 --> 00:01:53.580
and found that very many
of the basic things that we

00:01:53.580 --> 00:01:57.730
should do correctly for forms
are not being implemented.

00:01:57.730 --> 00:02:02.550
For example, we found
that 46% of top sites

00:02:02.550 --> 00:02:06.820
don't implement error
messaging in real time.

00:02:06.820 --> 00:02:10.050
So when users make an error,
they don't know about it

00:02:10.050 --> 00:02:13.170
until they go to hit the Submit
button, and then they're told.

00:02:13.170 --> 00:02:15.990
And then they have to look
for where that error is.

00:02:15.990 --> 00:02:18.600
It means that almost
half of the top sites

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:23.240
don't optimize their error
messaging for ease of use.

00:02:23.240 --> 00:02:28.220
And we found that 29% of sites
don't allow users to navigate

00:02:28.220 --> 00:02:31.040
back and forth in the flow--
perhaps in the checkout

00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:32.600
experience--

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:36.710
without losing information
that they've already entered.

00:02:36.710 --> 00:02:39.560
So these types of issues
lead to much frustration

00:02:39.560 --> 00:02:45.300
for users who are trying to
complete their transaction.

00:02:45.300 --> 00:02:48.360
So it's no wonder that
69% of digital carts

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:52.260
are abandoned before the
purchase has been completed.

00:02:52.260 --> 00:02:54.990
These numbers represent
a significant opportunity

00:02:54.990 --> 00:02:57.510
to improve the
experience for consumers

00:02:57.510 --> 00:02:59.560
and to create checkout
flows that bring

00:02:59.560 --> 00:03:03.060
delight in their simplicity.

00:03:03.060 --> 00:03:05.580
