So we're going to
talk about some

00:05:35.920 --> 00:05:38.560
of the best principles
that went into creating

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:42.370
Google Pay, the practices
around how you can develop

00:05:42.370 --> 00:05:45.820
great checkout experiences
with the system effectively,

00:05:45.820 --> 00:05:48.970
and a little bit about
how Google Pay is enabling

00:05:48.970 --> 00:05:52.940
assistive transactions
with voice.

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:56.360
Because consumer products
are dependent on the user

00:05:56.360 --> 00:06:00.080
experience, we started with
a user-focused approach

00:06:00.080 --> 00:06:02.650
to meet those needs.

00:06:02.650 --> 00:06:04.830
We began defining
an overall vision

00:06:04.830 --> 00:06:07.230
of what we wanted
to do to create

00:06:07.230 --> 00:06:11.550
safe and easy check out
experiences for everyone

00:06:11.550 --> 00:06:13.500
everywhere.

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:15.570
We informed our vision
through conducting

00:06:15.570 --> 00:06:19.950
foundational research and
then we carried our learnings

00:06:19.950 --> 00:06:23.430
from this into our design work.

00:06:23.430 --> 00:06:25.590
And then we iterated
on the designs,

00:06:25.590 --> 00:06:29.660
all infomed through user
testing and usability testing.

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:31.430
And we published
developer guidelines

00:06:31.430 --> 00:06:33.380
for our community of developers.

00:06:33.380 --> 00:06:36.140
We're continuing to update
and improve and optimize

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:38.880
our platform for consumers
and for developers.

00:06:38.880 --> 00:06:40.870
Let's look at this
user-centered approach

00:06:40.870 --> 00:06:43.295
again with more specifics
about the activities

00:06:43.295 --> 00:06:46.290
that we took for each phase.

00:06:46.290 --> 00:06:49.230
So our first step involved
conducting research

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:51.930
to understand the
broader picture,

00:06:51.930 --> 00:06:54.780
the users needs around
payments and their lives.

00:06:54.780 --> 00:06:57.720
And we visited different
regions across the globe.

00:06:57.720 --> 00:07:00.180
We went to Europe and
North and South America

00:07:00.180 --> 00:07:04.500
and we visited Asia and we
explored users payment methods

00:07:04.500 --> 00:07:07.920
and needs through
conducting research there.

00:07:07.920 --> 00:07:11.580
We learned about the importance
of speed and efficiency,

00:07:11.580 --> 00:07:13.710
security and privacy.

00:07:13.710 --> 00:07:16.440
And these learnings have
really shaped the design work

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:19.820
that we've done for Google Pay.

00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:23.120
Taking these learnings, we
established a set of principles

00:07:23.120 --> 00:07:27.350
and created a design system
that would meet those needs.

00:07:27.350 --> 00:07:31.370
And we tested our designs
with usability studies.

00:07:31.370 --> 00:07:34.310
In key phases of the
product development,

00:07:34.310 --> 00:07:36.920
we ran studies every
two weeks, iterating

00:07:36.920 --> 00:07:40.640
as we uncovered issues and
we could make improvements

00:07:40.640 --> 00:07:42.020
to the product.

00:07:42.020 --> 00:07:44.120
We dedicated ourselves
to the details

00:07:44.120 --> 00:07:46.620
and to getting it
right with our users.

00:07:46.620 --> 00:07:49.730
We also iterated through
conducting live experiments

00:07:49.730 --> 00:07:53.720
with our partners, and used
this data in a complementary way

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:57.970
to inform our design decisions.

00:07:57.970 --> 00:08:00.460
Based on all our learnings
throughout this process,

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:02.920
we published guidelines
for developers

00:08:02.920 --> 00:08:05.230
in order to take
advantage of this work

00:08:05.230 --> 00:08:09.805
and make implementation
clear and easy.

00:08:09.805 --> 00:08:12.430
BRANDON HERRING: So let's take
a look at some of the principles

00:08:12.430 --> 00:08:14.930
that we established that guided
us through the process Jenny

00:08:14.930 --> 00:08:17.150
just talked about.

00:08:17.150 --> 00:08:20.600
First and foremost,
Google Pay has to be fast.

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:22.670
We know users want a
quick and easy checkout

00:08:22.670 --> 00:08:25.240
flow and experience online.

00:08:25.240 --> 00:08:27.870
We want to remove that friction
with a lightweight UI that's

00:08:27.870 --> 00:08:31.500
super intuitive to use
and easy for users.

00:08:31.500 --> 00:08:33.180
And we've seen this in practice.

00:08:33.180 --> 00:08:34.679
With Game Time,
which is an app that

00:08:34.679 --> 00:08:37.470
lets users purchase tickets
for events and concerts

00:08:37.470 --> 00:08:40.620
they want to go to, Google
Pay is front and center

00:08:40.620 --> 00:08:43.890
the moment a user encounters
an event they want to attend.

00:08:43.890 --> 00:08:47.220
Even before they've signed in,
they're already ready to pay.

00:08:47.220 --> 00:08:50.460
Because of this, users can check
out and purchase their tickets

00:08:50.460 --> 00:08:52.350
in only two taps.

00:08:52.350 --> 00:08:55.250
Google Pay loads
a lightweight UI

00:08:55.250 --> 00:08:57.330
that shows them their
account, the payment

00:08:57.330 --> 00:08:58.560
method they're going to use.

00:08:58.560 --> 00:09:00.660
One more tap, they're done.

00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:03.330
It's really fast,
it's super easy.

00:09:03.330 --> 00:09:05.070
And that means for
Game Time users,

00:09:05.070 --> 00:09:07.611
all they really need to
worry about is whether or not

00:09:07.611 --> 00:09:10.110
their favorite team is going
to make the playoffs this year.

00:09:10.110 --> 00:09:15.320
And I'm optimistic about mine,
so fingers crossed there.

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:17.780
This is obviously
great for users,

00:09:17.780 --> 00:09:20.180
but this efficiency
also leads to results.

00:09:20.180 --> 00:09:23.480
Game Time found that
users who had Google Pay

00:09:23.480 --> 00:09:25.880
were two times higher
to convert than users

00:09:25.880 --> 00:09:28.260
who just had a payment
card saved to Game Time.

00:09:28.260 --> 00:09:30.800
So in other words,
even when the user

00:09:30.800 --> 00:09:33.470
has a payment method already
saved with a merchant,

00:09:33.470 --> 00:09:35.384
the seamlessness that
Google Pay can offer

00:09:35.384 --> 00:09:36.800
leads to a higher
conversion rate.

00:09:39.350 --> 00:09:41.590
The second principle
was around scale.

00:09:41.590 --> 00:09:43.600
So this meant a
few things to us.

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:45.820
We needed to address
a global audience,

00:09:45.820 --> 00:09:48.107
we needed to support a
variety of payment methods.

00:09:48.107 --> 00:09:49.690
We also needed to
create a place where

00:09:49.690 --> 00:09:52.180
users can update their payment
information once and have

00:09:52.180 --> 00:09:54.742
it available anywhere
they sign in.

00:09:54.742 --> 00:09:56.200
And of course, we
also need to make

00:09:56.200 --> 00:09:58.770
sure we're supporting more than
just the Android ecosystem,

00:09:58.770 --> 00:10:01.270
that we're across browser and
we're across OS, some of which

00:10:01.270 --> 00:10:04.180
we announced this week.

00:10:04.180 --> 00:10:07.650
So we have to enable users to
check out quickly and easily,

00:10:07.650 --> 00:10:09.090
no matter where they are.

00:10:09.090 --> 00:10:10.590
With our first
party integrations,

00:10:10.590 --> 00:10:13.470
we already support a wide
variety of payment methods.

00:10:13.470 --> 00:10:16.590
And we're bringing this
scalability to developers,

00:10:16.590 --> 00:10:19.139
letting users pick
however they want to pay,

00:10:19.139 --> 00:10:21.180
from leveraging all the
payment methods they have

00:10:21.180 --> 00:10:23.670
on file with Google
to new experiences,

00:10:23.670 --> 00:10:26.940
like eMoney for in-store in
Japan and Paypal for in-store.

00:10:29.740 --> 00:10:33.130
We make it really easy to
implement localized buttons.

00:10:33.130 --> 00:10:36.684
That lets developers
reach a global audience.

00:10:36.684 --> 00:10:38.850
And we've made it really
easy to manage your payment

00:10:38.850 --> 00:10:39.660
methods too.

00:10:39.660 --> 00:10:41.640
Now users can update
that information

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:44.910
in the Google Pay
app, iOS or Android,

00:10:44.910 --> 00:10:48.060
or on the Google Pay web and
have that immediately available

00:10:48.060 --> 00:10:49.867
anywhere they're signed in.

00:10:49.867 --> 00:10:51.450
This is a huge win
for users, but it's

00:10:51.450 --> 00:10:54.240
a really big win for
developers, because it ensures

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:56.160
that a user's payment
information is going

00:10:56.160 --> 00:10:58.590
to be available and
work on any app or site

00:10:58.590 --> 00:11:01.840
that they want to transact with.

00:11:01.840 --> 00:11:04.180
And of course, Google Pay
needs to work anywhere

00:11:04.180 --> 00:11:07.240
they can access their Google
account, so across operating

00:11:07.240 --> 00:11:09.250
systems from Android to iOS--

00:11:09.250 --> 00:11:11.470
which we just
announced-- and browsers

00:11:11.470 --> 00:11:14.650
beyond just Chrome, but into
Safari, Firefox, and more,

00:11:14.650 --> 00:11:16.300
enabling people to
check out regardless

00:11:16.300 --> 00:11:18.430
of browser preference
or device preference.

00:11:18.430 --> 00:11:20.554
This expands the reach
that developers have

00:11:20.554 --> 00:11:21.970
and it increases
the user benefit.

00:11:25.610 --> 00:11:28.340
JENNY GOVE: Now we know
from conducting research

00:11:28.340 --> 00:11:32.720
that one of the single
biggest concerns that users

00:11:32.720 --> 00:11:36.870
have with digital payments
is around security.

00:11:36.870 --> 00:11:38.810
And we've worked
hard to give users

00:11:38.810 --> 00:11:42.830
the security, transparency,
and control they need to feel

00:11:42.830 --> 00:11:45.680
confident in each transaction.

00:11:45.680 --> 00:11:48.090
The importance of
security, as I mentioned,

00:11:48.090 --> 00:11:52.160
comes up again and
again in user research.

00:11:52.160 --> 00:11:57.050
We know that it's both important
to be secure but also to convey

00:11:57.050 --> 00:11:59.240
that security to users.

00:11:59.240 --> 00:12:02.960
With Google Pay, we meet
these needs from the base up,

00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:05.270
from secure storage
infrastructure,

00:12:05.270 --> 00:12:08.390
card tokenization,
and authentication,

00:12:08.390 --> 00:12:11.210
through communications
such as notification

00:12:11.210 --> 00:12:14.910
and supplemental technologies
such as device security.

00:12:14.910 --> 00:12:17.240
So let's take a closer look.

00:12:17.240 --> 00:12:21.170
As you'd expect, Google Pay
rests on Google's secure data

00:12:21.170 --> 00:12:24.740
storage infrastructure, using
industry standard encryption

00:12:24.740 --> 00:12:27.920
to keep your payment
details safe.

00:12:27.920 --> 00:12:31.820
For transactions, we support
and encourage tokenization

00:12:31.820 --> 00:12:34.350
for install and
online use cases.

00:12:34.350 --> 00:12:37.890
Users transacting with cards
issued from supporting banks

00:12:37.890 --> 00:12:41.090
can tokenize these
in the Google Pay app

00:12:41.090 --> 00:12:43.730
and then transmit a
virtual account number--

00:12:43.730 --> 00:12:46.100
the token-- instead
of the real one

00:12:46.100 --> 00:12:48.500
when they pay at
participating merchants.

00:12:48.500 --> 00:12:51.890
We've also worked with payment
gateways and processors,

00:12:51.890 --> 00:12:56.530
to securely transmit
payment credentials online.

00:12:56.530 --> 00:12:59.290
But beyond the actual
underlying technology,

00:12:59.290 --> 00:13:01.600
it's important to
reinforce security

00:13:01.600 --> 00:13:03.520
through conveying
information about

00:13:03.520 --> 00:13:06.010
transactions transparently.

00:13:06.010 --> 00:13:08.740
We provide transaction
notifications

00:13:08.740 --> 00:13:11.230
for supporter cards,
so consumers know

00:13:11.230 --> 00:13:14.250
if a transaction is being made.

00:13:14.250 --> 00:13:16.440
Notifications is
just one of the ways

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:19.530
that we're communicating
transactions to users.

00:13:19.530 --> 00:13:22.170
We're also combining
